| &nbsp; || BGCOLOR="#F0D0D0" | <U+FF0F> || BGCOLOR="#F0D0D0" | <U+2502> || BGCOLOR="#F0D0D0" | <U+FF3C> || &nbsp;
|- align=center
| BGCOLOR="#F0D0D0" | <U+FF0F> || &nbsp; || BGCOLOR="#F0D0D0" | <U+2502> || &nbsp; || BGCOLOR="#F0D0D0" | <U+FF3C>
|}
|-
| colspan="4" bgcolor="#e0e0e0" width="50%" | '''Lion''' <U+2022> <U+7345><U+5B50> ''shishi''
|- 
| colspan="3" | <p align="justify">Area move/double capture: The lion can step one square in any direction up to twice in a turn. It can change directions after its first step, and is not restricted to following one of the eight orthogonal or diagonal directions. That is, it can also step to one of the in-between squares that a knight jumps to in Western chess.  
It can continue after a capture on the first step, potentially capturing two pieces on each turn.  
By moving back to its starting square, it can effectively capture a piece on an adjacent square without moving. This is called <U+5C45><U+55B0><U+3044> ''igui'' "stationary feeding".  
A similar move without capturing leaves the board unchanged, which is a way to pass a turn. 

Jump: The lion can jump anywhere within two squares. This is equivalent to jumping in any of the eight diagonal or orthogonal directions, or making any of the jumps of a knight in Western chess.

The lion does not promote. (KNADdK)
|
